Statistics with FPL | Scatter Plots

July 2024

Before trying to plot a graph, I need to load the packages I want to use (ggplot2 & dplyr, which are part of the tidyverse package), and download my data from vaastavs Fantasy-Premier-League GitHub page. This repository stores lots of FPL data from the last few seasons, which is very helpful!

library(tidyverse)

# Get data for all players
github <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/vaastav/Fantasy-Premier-League/master/data/2023-24/'
filenames <- sprintf("gw%s",seq(1:38))
PlayersList <- lapply(filenames, function(x) {
  data <- subset(read_csv(url(paste0(github, "gws/",x,".csv"))), minutes>0)
  return(data)}) 
PlayerData <- data.frame(data.table::rbindlist(PlayersList))

Next I want to inspect the data to see what kind of information we have:

Here I can see that for each player in each gameweek, including events like goals and clean sheets, statistics like xG, match info like kick-off time and opponent, and FPL-related data like price and position. So there is lots of information to make graphs from!

Before making any plots, I usually like to define a theme, which basically just changes the font style of all my plots so they all match each other! Here is my theme:

theme <- theme_classic() + theme(text = element_text(size = 12, family='Radio Canada Big'))

Here, theme_classic() gives the plot a minimalistic style, while element_text() modifies the font.

Scatter Plot: Are Price and Total Points Related?

To assess whether FPL price and total points are related, I could plot the starting price of a player against the total points scored across the whole season.

To do this, I first need to manipulate the data to get this information. Using the dplyr %>% (pipe) operator, I can filter the full dataset to get the GW1 prices for each player, and then group all the gameweeks together to get the total points for each player.

# Get gameweek 1 price for all players
GW1Prices <- PlayerData %>% filter(round==1) %>% select(name, team, position, value) %>% mutate(Value=value/10)
knitr::kable(head(GW1Prices))
name team position value Value
Jadon Sancho Man Utd MID 70 7.0
Vitaly Janelt Brentford MID 55 5.5
Andre Brooks Sheffield Utd MID 45 4.5
Curtis Jones Liverpool MID 50 5.0
Reece James Chelsea DEF 55 5.5
Ben Osborn Sheffield Utd MID 50 5.0 
# Get total points for all players
TotalPoints <- PlayerData %>% group_by(name) %>% summarise(Points=sum(total_points))
knitr::kable(head(TotalPoints))

Aaron Cresswell 10
Aaron Hickey 17
Aaron Ramsdale 20

Aaron Wan-Bissaka 47
Abdoulaye Doucour 116

Now I can merge the two tables together, and plot the data!

PriceTotalPoints <- merge(GW1Prices, TotalPoints)
knitr::kable(head(PriceTotalPoints))
name team position value Value Points
Aaron Hickey Brentford DEF 45 4.5 17
Aaron Ramsdale Arsenal GK 50 5.0 20
Aaron Wan-Bissaka Man Utd DEF 45 4.5 47
Abdoulaye Doucour Everton MID 55 5.5 116
Alejandro Garnacho Man Utd MID 50 5.0 131
Aleksandar Mitrovi Fulham FWD 75 7.5 1

To make a basic plot, I first specify the dataframe, x and y axes to ggplot(). Then I can add geom_point() to make a scatter graph (and my theme).

ggplot(data=PriceTotalPoints, aes(x=Value, y=Points)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme

While this graph shows a general positive correlation between value and points, this graph is a bit boring and its also not very useful. We can change this by adding colours and labels. For example, I could colour the players by their position, using scale_color_manual() to change the colour palette. I can also change the alpha level (transparency) and size of the points.

ggplot(data=PriceTotalPoints, aes(x=Value, y=Points, colour=position)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.75, size=5) +
  theme +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#a9c279', '#f6eb74', '#719fc0', '#f04d23'))

Now I can see that the majority of the low-scoring, low-value players are goalkeepers or defenders - however there are some outliers! Perhaps I can also select some players to label, so we can see who the best value players were last year. To do this I could divide total points by value:

PriceTotalPoints$PointsPerMillion <- round(PriceTotalPoints$Points/PriceTotalPoints$Value, 2)
knitr::kable(head(PriceTotalPoints %>% arrange(-PointsPerMillion)))
name team position value Value Points PointsPerMillion
Cole Palmer Man City MID 50 5.0 244 48.80

Benjamin White Arsenal DEF 55 5.5 182 33.09

Now I could label the 3 best value players on my graph:

# Get 10 best value players
Top10 <- PriceTotalPoints %>% arrange(-PointsPerMillion) %>% head(n=3)

# Add labels to dataframe
PriceTotalPoints$label <- ifelse(PriceTotalPoints$name %in% Top10$name, PriceTotalPoints$name, NA)

# Plot
ggplot(data=PriceTotalPoints, aes(x=Value, y=Points, colour=position, size=PointsPerMillion)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.75) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#a9c279', '#f6eb74', '#719fc0', '#f04d23'))+
  geom_label(aes(label=label), color='black', family='Radio Canada Big', size=4) +
  theme

Some of the labels on my plot are a bit messy - they are covering a lot of the points. I can use the package ggrepel to try and space the labels out so they are readable:

library(ggrepel)

# Plot
ggplot(data=PriceTotalPoints, aes(x=Value, y=Points, colour=position, size=PointsPerMillion)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.75) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c('#a9c279', '#f6eb74', '#719fc0', '#f04d23'))+
  geom_label_repel(aes(label=label), color='black', family='Radio Canada Big', nudge_x=6, box.padding = 0.3, size=4) +
  theme

Now we can see which 3 players had the best value last year!
